'''Andonios Liveralis''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: Αντώνιος Λιβεράλης or Λιμπεράλης, Italian: ''Antonio Liberali''; 1814 in [[Corfu]] &ndash; 1842 in Corfu) was a [[Greece|Greek]] conductor and composer of the early [[Ionian School (music)|Ionian school]]. He was the son of Italian conductor Domenico Liveralis and one of [[Nikolaos Mantzaros]]' favorite students.<ref name=Miroshnikov>{{cite book|last=Aleksei Miroshnikov|first=Natalia Miroshnikov|title=Light Under a Bushel, Piano works by greek composers 1847-1908|year=1999|publisher=Crete University Press|isbn=960-524-069-6|pages=7|url=http://www.greekfolkways.org/catalog/booklets/CUP11.PDF}}</ref> He later continued his studies at the [[Music conservatories of Naples#Conservatorio di San Pietro a Majella|Conservatory of San Pietro a Majella]] in [[Naples]].<ref name="Conferenza musicale mediterranea">{{cite book|last=Conferenza musicale mediterranea|title=MEMUS: mediterraneo musica : studi i documenti della Conferenza musicale mediterranea|year=1995|publisher=Regione Sicialiana|location=Palermo|pages=76|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=AIAaUO6xFc3MsgaLmoDgBA&hl=cs&id=0ulLAAAAYAAJ&dq=antonios+liveralis+San+Pietro+a+Majella&q=liveralis|language=it|OCLC=44798758}}</ref> When he returned to Corfu he was joyfully received into the circle of national composers, where he was considered a musician of great talent. He then began working as assistant to his teacher Mantzaros, who left him very little time for his own compositions. He was among the first teachers of his younger brother Iosif and served as vice director of music to the [[Philharmonic Society of Corfu]].<ref name=Miroshnikov/>
Liveralis' compositions are largely limited to minor forms. He wrote a series of fixed funeral marches, which were later published in two volumes. The march ''O Kambouris'' (Ο Καμπούρης, 'The Hunchback') achieved great popularity in Corfu. He also devoted himself to composing piano music and to the creation of a rich song repertoire. His one-act opera is the only sure finished work for the stage by the composer. He was born a Catholic, but was converted to [[Greek Orthodox]] faith and adopted the patriotic name of Eleftheriadis (Greek: Ελευθεριάδης). After his untimely death, he was buried in a magnificent funeral to which the orchestra of the [[Philharmonic Society of Corfu]] played.
